{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525022","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525022"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:11:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:11:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14045"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14045"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0,0.03,0.47,0.48]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6694"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50435"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6694","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6694"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14045"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35657"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"387"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"3051"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13830"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13834"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14231"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50435","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50435"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine check-up. He has a history of alcohol use disorder and currently drinks 6-8 standard drinks daily. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His most recent bloods showed mildly elevated GGT and AST and a ferritin of 303.  During the consultation, he states, \u0022I know my drinking is causing problems, and I should probably cut back, but I\u0027m not sure I\u0027m ready to change just yet. It helps me relax after work and I don\u0027t think it\u0027s really causing any harm.\u0022\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this patient\u0027s current stage of change?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Preparation","Action","Maintenance","Contemplation","Precontemplation"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question assesses understanding of the stages of change model, which is widely used in addiction treatment and behavior modification. The model includes five stages: \u003Cstrong\u003Eprecontemplation\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Econtemplation\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Epreparation\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eaction\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Emaintenance\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the patient is in the \u003Cstrong\u003Econtemplation\u003C/strong\u003E stage. He acknowledges that his drinking is problematic (\u0022I know my drinking is causing problems\u0022) and is considering change (\u0022I should probably cut back\u0022), but he is ambivalent and not yet ready to commit to change (\u0022but I\u0027m not sure I\u0027m ready to change just yet\u0022). This ambivalence is characteristic of the contemplation stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is not in \u003Cstrong\u003Eprecontemplation\u003C/strong\u003E because he recognizes that his drinking is problematic. In precontemplation, individuals typically deny they have a problem or are unaware that their behavior is causing issues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is not in the \u003Cstrong\u003Epreparation\u003C/strong\u003E stage because he hasn\u0027t made a commitment to change or started planning how to change. Preparation involves making a firm decision to change and beginning to make plans.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eaction\u003C/strong\u003E stage involves actively modifying behavior, which this patient is not yet doing. Similarly, \u003Cstrong\u003Emaintenance\u003C/strong\u003E involves sustaining behavior change over time, which is not applicable here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding a patient\u0027s current stage of change is crucial for healthcare providers to tailor their interventions appropriately. For a patient in contemplation, interventions might focus on exploring ambivalence, discussing the pros and cons of change, and providing information about treatment options.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The stages of change model includes precontemplation, contemplation, preparation, action, and maintenance.","Recognizing a patient\u0027s current stage of change is crucial for tailoring interventions in addiction treatment.","Patients in the contemplation stage acknowledge their problem but are ambivalent about making changes."],"references":["Health Promotion Unit, 2007. Stages of behaviour change: Queensland Stay On Your Feet.  Community Good Practice Toolkit. Division of Chief Health Officer, Queensland Health."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35657"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14045"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35657"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-11T22:22:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-12T11:56:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6694"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50435"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"descriptio